p>Summary</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>This position is located in the Domestic Relations Branch, Family Court Operations Division, Superior Court of the District of Columbia.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>The Domestic Relations Custody Assessor Supervisor supervises the Domestic Relations Custody Assessor and Domestic Relations Custody Investigator, conducts initial meetings with parents in domestic relations cases in which child custody is disputed, assesses the feasibility of mediation, and where indicated conducts investigations or custody assessments, including home and school visits and interviews with other family members to assemble a comprehensive report.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>The purpose of the position is to provide decision-making assistance regarding the aforementioned child to the judicial officer presiding over the case.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>The incumbent is an energetic, optimistic professional who enjoys working with a diverse group of Court personnel and customers and lives the DC Courtsâ values of Accountability, Excellence, Fairness, Integrity, Respect, and Transparency.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Duties</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF DUTIES: The work of the Custody Assessor Supervisor involves the effective supervision of the Custody Assessor and the Custody Investigator to accomplish the mission of the Domestic Relations Branch the screening of families, with domestic relations cases involving disputed child custody, to identify specific issues which may require fact finding investigation or assessment. Additionally, the work includes:</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Evaluating and implementing policies, procedures and best practices to improve the effectiveness and efficiency of the unit.</p><p>Collaborating with managers within the branch and from other branches and divisions as well as with other public and private agencies to coordinate mutual work-related programs and objectives of the court.</p><p>Supervision of conducted initial meetings with both parents in domestic relations cases with disputed custody to determine the feasibility of mediation to resolve the disputes.</p><p>Supervision of conducted investigations, at the home and school of the child, to include: objective observations about the childâs residence or another location that they frequent; interviews with parties to the case and other types of fact development as specifically ordered by the Court.</p><p>Conducting brief-focused assessments relative to the case, to include: Interviews with the parties and the child, where developmentally appropriate; Observations of the child with each party; Objective description concerning the needs of the child; Interviews with other appropriate individuals, such as adults living in a partyâs residence and Conduct other means of fact development as specifically ordered by the Court.</p><p>Reviewing collateral sources of information related to the care and well-being of the child, e.g., educational, medical and legal records pertinent to the issue of custody.</p><p>Maintaining appropriate case documentation, i.e., all contacts, documents or other possible forms of evidence on which an assessment could rely.</p><p>Approving written investigation/assessment reports within a time standard specified by the Order of Appointment.</p><p>Providing reports to all instructed parties and the Court as specified in the Order of Appointment.</p><p>Attending court hearings for the purpose of admitting a report and submitting to cross examination, when necessary.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Travel Required</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Occasional Travel</p><p>Travel within the D.C. Metropolitan area. Local travel includes but is not limited to: home and school visits.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Relocation Authorized</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>No</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Job Requirements</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Key Requirements</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>A background and/or security investigation is required.</p><p>Probationary period of one (1) year.</p><p>Fingerprinting and Child Registry Check.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Qualifications</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS:</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Master&#39;s of Social Work degree from an accredited program of social work under the Counsel of Social Work Education and an Independent Clinical Social Work License (LICSW) from the DC Board of Social Work (Department of Health, Health Professional Licensing Administration).</p><p>Three (3) years experience working in a social services environment performing activities such as assessments, evaluations or intake. Two (2) of your three (3) years of experience must be in an office setting, public service agency, court or legal environment.</p><p>One (1) year of supervisory experience or successful completion of the DC Courtsâ Management Training Program. Documentation of Education (copy of your academic transcript or degree) and Independent Clinical Social Work License (LICSW) must be submitted with your application or your application will not be considered.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Please note that authorization for the release of your adult criminal record revealing any convictions and forfeitures, and any criminal cases currently pending before the courts are required. If you are selected for the position, a criminal history records check will be conducted. This check will also include but is not limited to fingerprinting.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Upload a copy of your college transcript or degree. The transcript must show the name of the college or university, your name, list of courses with credit hours, major(s), and grade-point average or class ranking.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Foreign Education: Education completed outside the United States must have been evaluated by a private U.S. organization that specializes in interpretation of foreign educational credentials, commonly called a credential evaluation service or education to meet the above requirements.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>To qualify for this position, the following must be submitted:</p><p>1. R&#233;sum&#233;</p><p>2. Completed Vacancy Questionnaire</p><p>3. Documentation /Proof of Education (e.g. college transcript or degree)</p><p>4. Documentation / Proof of Professional License (LICSW)</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>To begin the process, click the Apply Online button to create an account or log in to your existing USAJOBS account. Follow the prompts to complete the vacancy questionnaire. Click the Submit My Answers button at the end of the process.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>All required documentation must be received by the closing date of the announcement.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>For more information about vacancies, e-mail at or call .</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Security Clearance</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Other</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Additional Information</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>What To Expect Next</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Once your completed application is received, your qualifications will be evaluated to determine your rating. The qualified candidates will be referred to the hiring manager for further consideration and possible interview. Once a selection is made all applicants will be notified of the outcome.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>BENEFITS</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>Other Information</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>This job is being filled by an alternative hiring process and is not in the competitive civil service.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>All required information must be received by the closing date.</p><p style="height:6px;"></p><p>This job originated on . For the full announcement and to apply, visit . Only resumes submitted according to the instructions on the job announcement listed at will be considere